		  <td class="forum_boardrow1" style="border-width: 0px 1px 1px 1px;" valign="top"><div id="message27775029">Magical realism is rarely used in anime as effectively as in this movie. Satoshi Kon leans toward it a lot, but it is only in this movie that it is actually fully utilized (Perfect Blue comes close). It has the reality-bending parts that his other works have, but in ways that don't affect things his other works do. The baby talking at the end, the "hostess" shining like an angel, the homeless girl's dream of home blending in with her current situation - these are all interesting examples of reality-bending, magical realism that make the movie clearly his while not making things ridiculous. Personally that touch is what made this a great Satoshi Kon movie.<br />
<br />
It's the idea of an ideal Christmas film taken to its logical conclusion, and I really think that's one of the greatest parts of this film. The other being also a Christmas film aspect once again used splendidly - the ragtag team of misfits who all come from different backgrounds is used to cross cultural and generational boundaries. It's a really endearing film that I think is worth a lot simply for its simplicity, and not in a way that Ghibli would make a film like that, but in a way only Satoshi Kon could.</div><div style="margin-top: 8px;"><em>Modified by NavyCherub, 01-20-14, 7:47 PM</em></div><div class="postActions"></div><div class="sig">&quot;My tables-meet it is I set it down<br />
That one may smile, and smile, and be a villain.&quot;</div></td>
